facts.text: Civil Appeal No. 58 of 1958 filed by decree-holders against judgment of Calcutta High Court dated April 5, 1955.

anchor.surface_text: CIVIL APPELLATE JURISDICTION Civil Appeal No. 58 of 1958. Appeal from the Judgment and decree dated April 5, 1955, of the Calcutta High Court in Appeal from Original Order No. 206 of 1953, arising out of the judgment and order dated May 20, 1953, of the Fourth Additional Sub-Judge, 24 Parganas at Alipore in Misc. Case No. 15 of 1951.

facts.text: Calcutta High Court judgment dated April 5, 1955 set aside order of Subordinate Judge dismissing objection of judgment-debtor.

anchor.surface_text: This appeal arises out of an execution proceeding. It is filed by the decree-holders and is directed against the judgment of the High Court at Calcutta setting aside the order of a learned Subordinate Judge at Alipore dismissing the objection of a judgment-debtor to the execution.

facts.text: Sukeshwari Ali possessed three plots of land Nos. 26, 27 and 28, Dum Dum Cossipore Road prior to 1944.

anchor.surface_text: The facts appear to have been as follows-One Sukeshwari Alied sometime prior to 1944 possessed of three plots of land which at all material times, bore premises Nos. 26, 27 and 28, Dum Dum Cossipore Road, in the outskirts of Calcutta.

facts.text: Sukeshwari left a will, defendants Nos. 1, 2 and 6 were executors who granted leases to defendants Nos. 3, 4 and 5.

anchor.surface_text: She left a will of which defendants Nos. 1, 2 and 6 were the executors. The executors granted leases of these different plots of land to defendants Nos. 3, 4 and 5 respectively and put them in possession.

facts.text: Mohatas filed suit on September 15, 1944 against executors and tenants for declaration of no right to possess and khas possession.

anchor.surface_text: Certain persons called Mohatas whose interests are represented by the appellants in the present appeal, claimed that Sukeshwari had only a life interest in the lands which on her death had vested in them and the executors had therefore no right to grant the leases. They filed a suit against the executors and the tenants on September 15, 1944

facts.text: Subordinate Judge at Alipore passed decree for khas possession in favour of Mohatas on March 30, 1948, giving six months to remove structures.

anchor.surface_text: On March 30, 1948, the learned Subordinate Judge passed a decree for khas possession in favour of the Mohatas and gave the defendants six months time to remove the structures put up on the land.

facts.text: Defendant No. 3 appealed and succeeded; no further concern with defendant No. 3 who possessed premises No. 26.

anchor.surface_text: Defendant No. 3 appealed from this decree and that appeal succeeded for reasons which do not appear on the record. ... It may however be stated that he was in possession of premises No. 26 and no application for execution appears to have been made against him.

facts.text: Defendant No. 4, Bengal Breweries Ltd., in possession of premises No. 27 with factory for distilling liquor and yeast.

anchor.surface_text: Of these tenants we are concerned only with defendant No. 4, the Bengal Breweries Ltd., a company carrying on business as distillers. It was in possession of premises No. 27, on which it had built a factory for distilling liquor and yeast.

facts.text: Mohatas filed execution application on September 22, 1948 against defendants Nos. 1,2,4,5,6.

anchor.surface_text: On September 22, 1948, the Mohatas the decree-holders, filed an application in the Court of the learned Subordinate Judge for execution of the decree against defendants Nos. 1, 2, 4, 5 6.

facts.text: Subordinate Judge issued writ for delivery of possession of premises Nos. 27 and 28 on September 25, 1948.

anchor.surface_text: On September 25, the learned Subordinate Judge passed an order in execution issuing a writ for delivery of possession of premises Nos. 27 and 28 to the decree-holders by removing, any person bound by the decree who refused to vacate the same and fixed November 22 for making the return to the writ.

facts.text: Execution carried out by Nazir on October 1, 1948; possession delivered to decree-holders for premises 27 and 28 with amicable settlement allowing defendant No. 4 to run business for 6 weeks and guards posted.

anchor.surface_text: On October 1, 1948, the Nazir of the Court proceeded to premises Nos. 27 and 28 with certain police officers to execute the decree in terms of the writ. ... We then entered into the factory house and delivered possession in each of the buildings at about 10-30 a. m. Before removal of the furniture and other movables from those buildings there was an amicable settlement between the decree-holders and the manager of the factory that the factory will run its normal business as before for 6 weeks

facts.text: Decree-holders executed receipt acknowledging delivery of possession on October 1, 1948 at 10:30 a.m.

anchor.surface_text: After possession had been delivered, the decree-holders executed on the same day a receipt in acknowledgment of possession having been received by them. That receipt is in these terms Received from Sri Bhabataran Banerjee, Naib Nazir, District Judges Court, Alipore, 24-Parganas, delivery of possession of premises Nos. 7 and 8 formerly Nos. 27 and 28 Dum Dum Cossipore Road

facts.text: Subordinate Judge ordered execution case dismissed on part satisfaction regarding Bengal Breweries on September 8, 1949.

anchor.surface_text: On September 8, 1949, the following order was made by the learned Subordinate Judge in the execution case Decree-holder takes no other steps. Possession so far as regards the Bengal Breweries are concerned, delivered. Ordered that the execution case be dismissed on part satisfaction.

facts.text: Decree-holders made fresh execution application against defendant No. 4 on September 27, 1951.

anchor.surface_text: On September 27, 1951, the decree-holders made a fresh application for execution against defendant No. 4 alone by evicting it from premises No. 27.

facts.text: Defendant No. 4 objected under s.47 alleging decree fully executed; Subordinate Judge dismissed objection on May 20, 1953.

anchor.surface_text: Defendant No. 4 put in an objection against the execution under s. 47 of the Code alleging that so far as it was concerned, the decree had been fully executed as a result of the earlier execution proceedings which terminated by the order of September 8, 1949

facts.text: High Court set aside Subordinate Judge's order and dismissed execution petition.

anchor.surface_text: As earlier stated, the learned Subordinate Judge dismissed the objection to the execution but on appeal the High Court set aside his order and dismissed the petition for execution.

facts.text: Defendant No. 4 executed first mortgage of premises No. 27 on May 25, 1944 to Coming Banking Corporation Ltd.

anchor.surface_text: It appears that defendant No. 4 had executed three successive mortgages of premises No. 27 with all structures and appurtenances, to a bank called the Coming Banking Corporation Ltd. The first of these mortgages had been executed on May 25, 1944

facts.text: United Bank obtained final mortgage decree on May 30, 1955, auctioned property on July 20, 1956, confirmed sale March 1, 1958, took possession, conveyed to added respondents on July 13, 1960.

anchor.surface_text: Some time in 1953, the United Bank filed a suit for enforcement of the mortgages. On May 30, 1955, a final mortgage decree was passed in favour of the United Bank. On July 20, 1956, the mortgaged properties were put up to auction and purchased by the United Bank. On March 1, 1958, the mortgage sale was confirmed and subsequently the United Bank was put in possession of premises No. 27. On July 13,1960, the United Bank Conveyed premises No. 27

facts.text: Supreme Court added Mool Chand Sethia, Tola Ram Sethia and Hulas Chand Bothra as respondents on August 11, 1960.

anchor.surface_text: On August 11, 1960, an order was made by this Court adding three persons named Mool Chand Sethia, Tola Ram Sethia and Hulas Chand Bothra as parties respondents to this appeal.

facts.text: Court found that decree was fully executed against defendant No. 4 on October 1, 1948 as possession delivered and receipt given.

anchor.surface_text: The records of the proceedings show that such possession was delivered. Defendant No. 4 was the party in possession and bound by the decree. ... The decree had therefore been satisfied in full as against the Bengal Breweries Ltd. and consequently as regards premises No. 27 in its possession.

facts.text: Executors' appeal dismissed on September 8, 1954.

anchor.surface_text: It does not appear from the records what other proceedings, if any, were taken in the appeal by the executor defendants but it is agreed that appeal was dismissed on September 8, 1954.

facts.text: High Court granted certificate for appeal to Supreme Court on June 15, 1956.

anchor.surface_text: The High Court granted a certificate for an appeal to this Court on June 15, 1956 and on August 3, 1956, the High Court passed an order directing that the appeal be admitted.

It was there said at p. 15, The case, therefore, seems to me to be one of those cases in which a decree-holder having armed himself with a decree for khas possession executes that decree in the first instance by obtaining symbolical possession only with some ulterior object of his own, and thereafter subsequently and as a second instalment asks for khas possession.

precedents.cited_proposition: decree for khas possession executed by obtaining symbolical possession only cannot be subsequently executed for khas possession
precedents.cited_holding: The case, therefore, seems to me to be one of those cases in which a decree-holder having armed himself with a decree for khas possession executes that decree in the first instance by obtaining symbolical possession only with some ulterior object of his own, and thereafter subsequently and as a second instalment asks for khas possession. The question is whether such a course is permissible under the law. I am of opinion that it is not.
